You’re landing on something that cognitive science, linguistics, and AI all converge on:

Memory and meaning are relational, not just symbolic.

Words don’t carry meaning by themselves — they anchor into a network of relationships. That’s exactly why semantics works as the compression layer of language.

Let’s translate your idea into a usable “math of meaning for language.”

⸻

1. Memory is relationally weighted

In cognitive science, memory behaves like a weighted network.

Concepts are nodes, relationships are edges, and edges have strengths.

Example:

fire → heat (0.9)
fire → danger (0.8)
fire → cooking (0.6)
fire → warmth (0.7)

Meaning is the pattern of connections, not the word itself.

This is why hearing “fire” activates a whole cluster of related ideas.

⸻

2. Semantics as anchor points

Your idea that semantics anchors meaning is very accurate.

A semantic anchor is a stable reference concept.

Examples:

anchor	meaning cluster
time	past, future, change
space	location, movement
agent	actor, intention
object	thing acted upon
cause	why something happens

These anchors function like constants in language.

⸻

3. Language compression

Human language is extremely compressed.

Instead of saying:

the agent caused the object to change state through applied force

we say:

“He pushed it.”

One short phrase encodes:
	•	actor
	•	action
	•	object
	•	causality
	•	motion

Language works because shared semantic anchors decompress the meaning.

⸻

4. The relational weighting principle

Meaning strength comes from how strongly nodes connect.

In mathematical terms you can represent it as a matrix:

W_{ij}

Where:
	•	i and j are concepts
	•	W is the relationship weight.

This is essentially how modern language models represent meaning internally.

⸻

5. Meaning emerges from context

A word’s meaning shifts depending on surrounding relationships.

Example:

“bank”

context	meaning
river	riverbank
money	financial bank
airplane	banking turn

Context changes the active semantic neighborhood.

⸻

6. Efficient language design

If you wanted to optimize language using your framework, you’d aim for:

high compression

Few symbols representing large semantic clusters.

low ambiguity

Clear anchors so meaning resolves quickly.

relational clarity

Explicit links between ideas.

Many technical languages (math, programming) do this deliberately.

⸻

7. Constants of language

Earlier we talked about mathematical constants.

Language has something similar: semantic primitives.

Examples:

primitive	function
entity	something exists
action	something changes
relation	connection between things
time	ordering of events
negation	absence

Every sentence decomposes into these.

⸻

8. Meaning as geometry

You can imagine meaning as movement through semantic space.

Sentence example:

The cat chased the mouse.

Path:

agent → action → object.

The geometry of that path defines meaning.

⸻

9. Adaptability of language

Because meanings are relational, languages can evolve without breaking.

Words shift meaning but the underlying relational structure stays intact.

Example:

“mouse”

animal → computer device.

The network expands rather than replacing the old meaning.

⸻

10. The hunter analogy again

Your earlier metaphor still works well.

Semantic anchors act like visual landmarks.

The brain scans for:
	•	stable structures
	•	deviations
	•	relationships.

That’s how humans rapidly parse meaning in conversation.

⸻

✅ Condensed insight

Language efficiency comes from:
	•	semantic anchors
	•	relational weighting
	•	contextual activation.

Meaning isn’t in the word — it’s in the network around the word.

